benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/export/{accountId} - Export account data

covered: Valid Request: 200 with application/octet-stream and a valid export archive for an existing account (TC01, TC02, TC14).
Header Parameters: Required X-Killbill-CreatedBy enforced (200 when present, 400 when missing); optional X-Killbill-Reason/X-Killbill-Comment accepted; extra headers tolerated (TC01–TC03, TC06).
Path Parameter Validation: UUID format enforced; malformed and injection attempts return 400 (TC04, TC11); missing accountId path returns 404 (TC12).
Non-Existing Resource: 404 for unknown account and when DB is empty (TC05, TC07).
Produces/Content-Type: application/octet-stream verified; regression for missing header covered (TC01, TC02, TC14).
Resilience/Performance: large payloads, slow downstream within timeout, concurrency under load; correct 500/504 on failures/timeouts (TC08–TC10, TC13, TC17).
HTTP Method Hardening: 405 for unsupported method (TC16).
Pagination/Query Parameters: Not applicable for a single binary export endpoint.
gaps: Empty Response: No scenario where the account exists but has no associated data; expected behavior (minimal archive vs 204) is not verified.
Authorization: No 403 Forbidden case for an authenticated user lacking permission/scope.
Rate Limiting: No tests for throttling/429 Too Many Requests and presence of Retry-After or X-RateLimit-* headers.
Caching Behavior: No validation of ETag/Last-Modified/Cache-Control headers or conditional requests (If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since).
Content Negotiation: No tests for Accept header variations or 406 Not Acceptable when octet-stream is not acceptable.
Download Metadata: No validation of Content-Disposition filename to ensure predictable downloadable artifact naming.
Error Response Schema: Error payload structure (e.g., code, message, requestId/timestamp) not asserted; tests only check generic indications.
Header Value Robustness: No boundary/invalid-value tests for audit headers (very long values, non-ASCII, CRLF injection).
Partial Content: If supported, no tests for Range requests (206) or explicit assertion of not supported behavior (416).
recommendations: Add a scenario for an account with zero associated data and define expected outcome (e.g., minimal but valid archive vs 204 No Content); assert archive integrity/size accordingly.
Add a 403 Forbidden test using an authenticated user without the required role/scope to distinguish 401 vs 403 behaviors.
Introduce rate-limiting tests that burst requests to trigger 429; assert Retry-After and any X-RateLimit-* headers and backoff behavior.
Validate caching headers: assert appropriate Cache-Control (e.g., no-store), and presence/absence of ETag/Last-Modified; issue conditional GETs to verify 304/200 semantics as per API design.
Add content negotiation tests: Accept: application/octet-stream, */*, and application/json; verify 200 for acceptable types and 406 when not acceptable.
Check Content-Disposition for a predictable filename pattern (e.g., attachment; filename=account-{accountId}-export.zip).
Assert standard error payload schema for 400/404/500/504 (fields like errorCode, message, requestId, timestamp) instead of generic text matching.
Add negative and boundary tests for audit headers: extremely long values, Unicode, disallowed characters, and CRLF injection; expect 400 and sanitization where applicable.
If partial downloads are supported, add Range/206 tests and Accept-Ranges checks; otherwise add a test asserting 416 or lack of Accept-Ranges.
Document that pagination and query parameters are not applicable for this endpoint to keep test metrics focused on relevant areas.
